# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-condon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Grouès was born on 5 August 1912 in Lyon, France to a wealthy Catholic family of silk traders, the fifth of eight children.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The writer and murderer Héra Mirtel was one of his aunts.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He spent his childhood in Irigny, near Lyon.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was twelve when he met François Chabbey and went for the first time with his father to an Order circle, the brotherhood of the "*Hospitaliers veilleurs*" in which the mainly middle-class members would serve the poor by providing barber services.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Grouès became a member of the *Scouts de France* in which he was nicknamed "Meditative Beaver" (*Castor méditatif*).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1928, aged 16, he made the decision to join a monastic order, but he had to wait until he was seventeen and a half to fulfill this ambition.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1931, Grouès entered the Capuchin Order, renouncing his inheritance and offering all his possessions to charity.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Known as *frère Philippe* (Brother Philippe), he entered the monastery of Crest in 1932, where he lived for seven years and was ordained a priest on 24 August 1938.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He had to leave in 1939 after developing severe lung infections, which made monastic life difficult.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He became a chaplain to the sick at several places and then was made curate of Grenoble's cathedral in April 1939.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The theologian Henri de Lubac told him on the day of his priestly ordination: "Ask the Holy Spirit to grant you the same anti-clericalism of the saints".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] When World War II broke out in 1939, he was mobilised as a non-commissioned officer in the train transport corps.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] According to his official biography, he helped Jewish people to escape Nazi persecution following the July 1942 mass arrests in Paris, called the *Rafle du Vel' d'Hiv*, and another raid in the area of Grenoble in the non-occupied zone: "In July 1942, two fleeing Jews asked him for help.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Having discovered the persecution taking place, he immediately went to learn how to make false passports.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Starting in August 1942, he guided Jewish people to Switzerland".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His pseudonym dates from his work with the French Resistance during the Second World War, when he operated under several different names.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Based in Grenoble, an important center of the Resistance, he helped Jews and politically persecuted escape to Switzerland.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1942, he assisted Jacques de Gaulle (the brother of Charles de Gaulle) and his wife escape to Switzerland.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He participated in establishing a section of the *maquis* where he officially became one of the local leaders in the Vercors Plateau and in the Chartreuse Mountains.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He helped people to avoid being taken into the *Service du travail obligatoire* (STO), the Nazi forced-labour program agreed upon with Pierre Laval, by creating in Grenoble the first refuge for resistants to the STO; he founded the clandestine newspaper *L'Union patriotique indépendante*.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] For a time, in 1943, he was given shelter by Lucie Coutaz, a Resistance member who later became his secretary and was his assistant in his charity work until her death in 1982.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was arrested twice, once in 1944 by the Nazi police in the town of Cambo-les-Bains in the Pyrénées-Atlantiques, but was quickly released and travelled to Spain then Gibraltar before joining the Free French Forces of General de Gaulle in Algeria.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In the Free North Africa, he became a chaplain in the French Navy on the battleship *Jean Bart* in Casablanca.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He had become an important symbol of the French Resistance.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1946, he was re-elected as a member of the National Assembly, but this time as a member of the MRP.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Abbé Pierre became vice-president of the World Federalist Movement in 1947, a universal federalist movement.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He then joined the Christian socialist movement named *Ligue de la jeune République*, created in 1912 by Marc Sangnier, but decided to finally end his political career.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1951, before the end of his mandate, he returned to his first vocation: helping the homeless.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] With the modest funds he had received as a deputy, he invested in a run-down house near Paris in the Neuilly-Plaisance neighbourhood, repairing the whole house.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He made it the first Emmaus base (because, according to him, it was simply too big for one person).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Although the priest had left representative politics, preferring to invest his energies in the Emmaus charity movement, he never completely abandoned the political field, taking strong stances on many and various subjects.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Thus, when the decolonization movement was slowly beginning to emerge in the whole world, he attempted in 1956 to convince Tunisian leader Habib Bourguiba to obtain independence without using violence.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Present in various international conferences at the end of the 1950s, he met Colombian priest Camilo Torres (1929–1966), a predecessor of Liberation theology, who asked for his advice on the Colombian Church's criticism of "workers' priests".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was also received by US president Eisenhower and Mohammed V of Morocco in 1955 and 1956.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1962, he resided for several months in Charles de Foucauld's retreat in Béni-Abbés (Algeria).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Abbé Pierre was then called to India in 1971 by Jayaprakash Narayan to represent, along with the *Ligue des droits de l'homme* (Human Rights League) France in the issues of refugees.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Indira Gandhi then invited him to deal with the question of Bengali refugees, and Grouès founded Emmaus communities in Bangladesh.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Emmaus (*Emmaüs* in French) was started in 1949.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Its name is a reference to a village in Palestine appearing in the Gospel of Luke, where two disciples extended hospitality to Jesus just after his resurrection without recognizing him.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In that way, Emmaus's mission is to help poor and homeless people.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1950 the first community of Emmaus companions was created in Neuilly-Plaisance close to Paris in France.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Emmaus community raises funds for the construction of housing by selling used goods.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] "Emmaus, it's a little like the wheelbarrow, the shovels and the pickaxes coming before the banners.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] A sort of social fuel derived from salvaging defeating men".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Grouès became famous during the extremely cold winter of 1954 in France, when homeless people were dying in the streets.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He went on to describe the drama of homeless life, claiming that in "every town in France, in every quarter of Paris" ministry was needed based on "these simple words: 'If you suffer, whoever you are, enter, eat, sleep, recover hope, here you are loved'".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The next morning, the press wrote of an "uprising of kindness" (*insurrection de la bonté*) and the now-famous call for help ended up raising 500 million francs in donations (Charlie Chaplin gave 2 million).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] This enormous amount was totally unexpected; telephone operators and the postal service were overwhelmed, and owing to the volume of donations, several weeks were needed just to sort them, distribute them, and find a place to stock them throughout the country.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Moreover, this call attracted volunteers from all over the country to help them, including wealthy *bourgeoises* who were emotionally shaken by the Abbé's call: first to do the redistribution, but then to duplicate the effort all around France.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Quite quickly, Grouès had to organise his movement by creating the *Emmaus communities* on 23 March 1954.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] A book was written by Boris Simon called *Abbé Pierre and the ragpickers of Emmaus*.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] It spread knowledge about the Emmaus community.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1955, the priest gave President Eisenhower an English translation of the book in the oval office.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Emmaus communities quickly spread worldwide.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Grouès traveled to Beyrouth (Beirut, Lebanon) in 1959, to assist in the creation of the first multiconfessional Emmaus group there; it was founded by a Sunni (Muslim), a Melkite (Catholic) archbishop and a Maronite (Christian) writer.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The same year, he organized the operation "Charity Christmas", which, relayed by *France Soir*, raised 6 million francs and 200 tons of products.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The actor Coluche, who had organized the charitable *Restos du Cœur*, offered him 150 million French cents received by his organisation.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Italian magistrate Carlo Mastelloni recalled in the *Corriere della Sera* in 2007 that a niece of the Abbé was a secretary at Hyperion language school in Paris, directed by Vanni Mulinaris, and married to one of the Italians refugees then wanted by the Italian justice.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] According to the *Corriere della Sera*, it would even have been him who convinced then president François Mitterrand to grant protection from extradition to left-wing Italian activists who took refuge in France and had broken with their past.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] More than 20 years later, the ANSA, Italian press agency, recalled that he had supported in 2005 one of his physicians, Michele d'Auria, who was a former member of *Prima Linea*, an Italian far-left group, and was accused of having participated in hold-ups during 1990.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Like many other Italian activists, he had exiled himself to France during the "years of lead", and then joined the Emmaus companions.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] *La Repubblica* specified that Italian justice has recognized the innocence of all people close to the Hyperion School.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In the 1990s, the Abbé criticized the apartheid regime in South Africa.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1995, after a three-year-long siege of Sarajevo, he went there to exhort nations of the world to put an end to the violence, and requested French military operation against the Serb positions in Bosnia.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] During the Gulf War (1990–91), Abbé Pierre directly addressed himself to US President George H.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He asked French president François Mitterrand to engage himself in matters concerning refugees, in particular by the creation of a stronger organisation than the current UN High Commissioner for Refugees (HCR).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He encountered this year the Dalai Lama during inter-religious peace encounters.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] A staunch supporter of the Palestinian cause, he has attracted attention with some of his statements on the Israeli-Palestine conflict.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His support "à titre amical" ("in title of friendship") for Roger Garaudy in 1996 brought controversy.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] But Garaudy provoked public indignation when he announced in March that he was supported by the Abbé Pierre, who was immediately excluded from the honour committee of the LICRA (International League against Racism and Anti-Semitism).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Abbé condemned those who tried to "negate, banalize or falsify the Shoah", but his continued support to Garaudy as a friend was criticized by all anti-racist, Jewish organisations (MRAP, CRIF, Anti-Defamation League, etc.) and the Church hierarchy.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His friend Bernard Kouchner, co-founder of Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF), criticized him for "absolving the intolerable", while Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger (and archbishop of Paris from 1981 to 2005) publicly disavowed him.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Abbé then went into retreat in the Benedictine monastery of Praglia near Padua, Italy.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In the film documentary *Un abbé nommé Pierre, une vie au service des autres*, the Abbé declared that his support had been towards the person of Roger Garaudy, and not towards statements in his book, which he had not read.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The curator of the Deportation and Resistance Museum of the Isère department where Grouès carried out most of his resistance activities declared that Abbé Pierre would have merited ten times to be named Righteous Among the Nations for his struggle in favor of Jews during Vichy.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Following this 1996 controversial support to a personal acquaintance, the Abbé was shunned for a period by the media, although Grouès remained a popular figure.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Abbé's positions towards the Church and the Vatican also brought controversy.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His positions on social issues and engagements were at times explicitly socialist and opposed to the Church.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He maintained a relationship with the progressive French Catholic Bishop Jacques Gaillot, to which he recalled his duty of "instinct of a measured insolence".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He did not like Mother Teresa; despite her work for the poor, her strict adherence to Catholic teaching on morality did not sit well with Abbé Pierre's left wing ideology.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He had difficult relations with the Vatican.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] *L'Osservatore Romano*, known for reporting the deaths of priests, did not report on his death right away in 2007.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Even though it is not customary for the Pope to offer condolences on the death of individual priests, Abbé Pierre's supporters were heavily critical of Pope Benedict XVI for not making an exception.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Father Lombardi, spokesman of the Vatican, pointed journalists to the statement made by the French Church, while Benedict XVI did mention his death in private audiences.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Official reactions from the Church came in two interviews of French cardinals, Roger Etchegaray and Paul Poupard.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His criticisms of what he considered the lavish lifestyle of the Vatican got him a lot of publicity (especially when he reproached John Paul II for his expensive travels), but were not well received by the public.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Cardinal Secretary of State Tarcisio Bertone lauded his "action in favor of poor": "Informed of the death of Abbe Pierre, the Holy Father gives thanks for his activity in favor of the poorest, by which he bore witness to the charity that comes from Christ.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Entrusting to divine mercy this priest whose whole life was dedicated to fighting poverty, he asks the Lord to welcome him into the peace of His kingdom.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] By way of comfort and hope, His Holiness sends you a heartfelt apostolic blessing, which he extends to the family of the departed, to members of the communities of Emmaus, and to everyone gathering for the funeral".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] His support for the ordination of women and for married clergy put him at odds with Catholic tradition, Church leaders and a substantial portion of French Catholics that followed the traditional teaching of the Church.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The same stances, according to British state media, made him popular among the declining number of left-wing Catholics in France.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In his book *Mon Dieu... pourquoi?* (God...
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Why?, 2005), co-written with Frédéric Lenoir, he admitted to breaking his solemn promise of celibacy by having had casual sex with women.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Despite very strong grassroots opposition to adoption by same-sex couples, Abbé Pierre dismissed people's concerns that it deprives children of a mother or father and turns them into objects.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Abbé also opposed the traditional Catholic policy on contraceptives.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was one of the signatories of the agreement to convene a convention for drafting a world constitution.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] As a result, for the first time in human history, a World Constituent Assembly convened to draft and adopt a Constitution for the Federation of Earth.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Abbé Pierre had the distinction of having been voted France's most popular person for many years, though he was surpassed in 2003 by Zinedine Zidane, moving to second place.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 2005, Abbé Pierre came third in a television poll to choose *Le Plus Grand Français* (The Greatest Frenchman).
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1992, Pierre was awarded the Grand Officer of the National Order of the Legion of Honour.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He refused the award, explaining in a letter addressed to Pierre Bérégovoy that he would refuse as long as "the automatic allocation of vacant premises had not put an end to the suffering of the homeless [...] Honour demands that those who suffer most should be served first.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 1998, he has been made Grand Officer of the National Order of Quebec while in 2004, he was awarded the Grand Cross of the Legion of Honor by Jacques Chirac.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He also received the Balzan Prize for Humanity, Peace and Brotherhood among Peoples in 1991 "For having fought, throughout his life, for the defence of human rights, democracy and peace.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] For having entirely dedicated himself to helping to relieve spiritual and physical suffering.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] For having inspired – regardless of nationality, race or religion – universal solidarity with the Emmaus Communities".
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was often sick, particularly in the lungs when he was young.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Abbé Pierre remained active until his death on 22 January 2007 in the Val-de-Grâce military hospital in Paris, following a lung infection, aged 94.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He took a stance on most social struggles: supporting illegal aliens, assisting the homeless on the "Enfants de Don Quichotte" movement (end of 2006–start of 2007) and social movements in favor of requisitioning empty buildings and offices (squats), etc.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He continued to read *La Croix*, the Catholic social newspaper every day.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In January 2007, he went to the National Assembly to lobby for a law on lodging homeless people.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] Following his death, the Minister of Social Cohesion Jean-Louis Borloo (UMP) decided to give Abbé Pierre's name to the law, despite the latter's scepticism of the law's real value.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In 2005 he opposed conservative deputies who wanted to reform the Gayssot Act on housing projects (*loi SRU*), which would have imposed a 20% housing project limit in each town.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] After homage by dignitaries, several hundred ordinary Parisians (among them professor Albert Jacquard, who worked with the abbé for the cause of homelessness) went to the Val-de-Grâce chapel to pay their respects.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] He was buried in a cemetery in Esteville, a small village in Seine-Maritime where he once lived.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In July 2024, the Fondation Abbé Pierre and Emmaus issued a statement about the results of an investigation they had commissioned after reports of abuse by Pierre had come to light.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] An independent research group reported that seven women (one of them a minor at the time of abuse) gave testimony about abuse they suffered at the hands of the French priest between the late 1970s and 2005.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] In September 2024, a report commissioned by the Fondation reported that Abbé Pierre sexually harassed or assaulted at least two dozen women.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] An 8–9 year child was also allegedly abused.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The abuse happened in France and in the United States.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The second report led the Abbé Pierre Foundation being retitled, and Emmaus France voting on removing the priest's name from its logo.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] The Abbé Pierre Centre in Esteville in Normandy, where he lived for many years and is buried, was to close, and the disposal of hundreds of statuettes, busts and other images of the charity's creator was discussed.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] There was evidence that colleagues in Emmaus and the Catholic Church knew about Abbé Pierre's sexual behaviour, but did not speak out.
[src:edward-condon/abbé-pierre] On 14 January 2025, the Bishops' Conference of France took legal action after the nine new accusations of sexual violence, in order to request the opening of an investigation.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] Jaffar was born on 9 August 1909 in Poona.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] His father Sir Ebrahim Haroon Jaffer was a businessman.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] He studied at Anglo Urdu Boys' High School and Deccan College.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] Jaffar was elected to the Central Legislative Assembly in 1934.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] In 1945, he was elected to the Central Legislative Assembly of India from Bombay.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] He was one of two representatives of the Muslim community from the Bombay Presidency.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] He served as the deputy whip of the All India Muslim League in the Central Legislative Assembly.After the Partition of India, Jaffar served as the President of the Pakistan Chamber of Film Industry.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] From 1948 to 1950, he was the president of Pakistan Olympic Association.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] Jaffar was a member of the Constituent Assembly of Pakistan.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] From 1947 to 1955, he served in the Parliament of Pakistan.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] He also incorporated his family business, founded in 1849 in Pune, in Karachi in 1948.
[src:edward-condon/ahmed-ebrahim-haroon-jaffer] As a result, for the first time in human history, a World Constituent Assembly convened to draft and adopt the Constitution for the Federation of Earth.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] Akira Kazami was born in Mitsukaido, Ibaraki Prefecture (present-day Jōsō, Ibaraki Prefecture).
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In 1905, he entered Waseda University where he joined the honorary school of Sugiura Jūgō.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In 1913, Kazami joined *Osaka Asahi Shimbun* (currently part of *The Asahi Shimbun*) and spent his life working as a journalist for Kokusai Tsushin and The Shinano Mainichi Shimbun.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] Kazami was a candidate in the 1928 Japanese general election, though he was not elected.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] However, in the 1930 general election he was elected for the first time and entered the Constitutional Democratic Party.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] He joined the Kokumin Dōmei in 1932 but left the party in 1936 to become independent.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] From no great prominence, he was made Secretary-General of the First Konoe Cabinet in 1937.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] He had been part of Konoe's think tank, the *Shōwa Kenkyūkai*, for a number of years.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] He held the position until January 1939.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In the 1940 Second Konoe Cabinet, he was Minister of Justice during the second half of the year but resigned after five months in office.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] After his resignation, he quit his political career to become a farmer.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] Following the end of the Second World War, he was purged until 1951.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In 1952, he returned to politics and was elected to the House of Representatives as an independent.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In 1955, he joined the Japan Socialist Party.
[src:edward-condon/akira-kazami] In 1960, he took part in the Anpo protests.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Humans have lived in the Alamogordo area for at least 11,000 years.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The present settlement, established in 1898 to support the construction of the El Paso and Northeastern Railroad, is an early example of a planned community.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Tourism became an important economic factor with the creation of White Sands National Park in 1933, which is still one of the biggest attractions of the city today.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] During the 1950s and 1960s, Alamogordo was an unofficial center for research on pilot safety and the development of the United States' space program.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo is a charter city with a council-manager form of government.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Gerald Champion Regional Medical Center is a nonprofit shared military/civilian facility that is also the hospital for Holloman Air Force Base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Tularosa Basin has been inhabited for at least 11,000 years.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are signs of previous inhabitants in the area such as the Clovis culture, the Folsom culture, the peoples of the Archaic period, and the Formative stage.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Mescalero Apache were already living in the Tularosa Basin when the Spanish came in 1534, and Mescalero oral history says they have always lived there.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 1719, the Spanish built a chapel at La Luz (about 5 miles (8.0 km) from the future site of Alamogordo), although La Luz was not settled until about 1860.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The city of Alamogordo was founded in June 1898, when the El Paso and Northeastern Railroad, headed by Charles Bishop Eddy, extended the railway to the town.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Eddy influenced the design of the community, which included large, wide thoroughfares and tree-lined irrigation canals.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Charles Eddy's brother, John Arthur Eddy, named the new city.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] He created a neologism adapted from the Spanish words for "large/fat cottonwood" after a grove of stout cottonwoods he remembered from the Pecos River area.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] However, the word "Alamogordo" was not used in the Spanish language.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] When Alamogordo was laid out in 1898, the east–west streets were given numerical designations, while north–south streets were named after states.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The present-day White Sands Boulevard was then called Pennsylvania Avenue.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] With the creation of White Sands National Monument in 1934, tourism began.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Works Progress Administration, a government program created in 1935 in response to the Great Depression, was responsible for the construction of several government buildings in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] These include the Otero County Administration Building at 1101 New York Avenue, a Pueblo style building originally constructed as the main U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The building is listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The main entrance portico features frescoes by Peter Hurd, which were completed in 1942.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In July 1941, the Alamogordo Bombing and Gunnery Range was established.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Post Office moved out in 1961, and the building was used by a succession of federal agencies and was known as the Federal Building.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The last federal agency to occupy it was the United States Forest Service who used it as the headquarters of the Lincoln National Forest until October 2008, when that agency moved to a newly constructed building.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In February 2009, ownership of the building was transferred to Otero County government and many government offices were moved from the Courthouse to its new Administration Building .
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 1983, Atari, Inc. buried more than 700,000 unsold Atari 2600 video game cartridges in Alamogordo's landfill.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Most notably, Atari discarded many copies of the unpopular *E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial*.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] This event was often believed to be an urban legend, until it was confirmed by Atari and excavations at the landfill.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo briefly made international news in late 2001 when Christ Community Church held a public book burning of books in the Harry Potter series, and several other series, on December 30.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of 2010, Alamogordo had a total area of 19.3 square miles (50.0 km2), all land.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The city is located on the western flank of the Sacramento Mountains and on the eastern edge of the Tularosa Basin.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It lies within the Rio Grande rift and in the northernmost part of the Chihuahuan Desert.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Tectonic activity is low in the Tularosa Basin.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Plants native to the area are typical of the southern New Mexico foothills and include creosote bush, mesquite, saltbush, cottonwood, desert willow, and many species of cactus and yucca.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Tularosa Basin is an endorheic, or closed, basin; that is, no water flows out of it.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Because of this and because of the geology of the region, water in the basin is hard: it has very high total dissolved solids concentrations, in excess of 3,000 mg/L.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Brackish Groundwater National Desalination Research Facility, a Bureau of Reclamation laboratory doing research and development on desalination of brackish water, is located in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The gypsum crystals of White Sands National Park are formed in Lake Lucero.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Water drains from the mountains carrying dissolved gypsum and collects in Lake Lucero.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] After the water dries, the winds pick up the gypsum crystals and distribute them over the basin.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo has a semi-arid climate (Köppen *BSk*), bordering a desert climate (*BWk*), with hot summers and mild winters.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Rainfall is low and usually confined to the monsoon from July to September, when half a typical year's rainfall of 10.63 in (270.0 mm) will occur – although December 1991 did see 5.45 in (138.4 mm).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The wettest calendar year has been 1941 with 21.87 in (555.5 mm) and the driest 1952 with 4.85 in (123.2 mm), while the wettest month on record has been September 1941 when 6.94 in (176.3 mm) fell.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] September 1941 also saw the largest daily rainfall at Alamogordo with 2.60 in (66.0 mm) falling on the 22nd of that month.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Temperatures outside of monsoonal storms are very hot during the summer: 89.1 days exceed 90 °F (32.2 °C) and temperatures as high as 110 °F (43.3 °C) occurred on June 22, 1981, and July 8, 1951.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Snow is very rare, with a mean of no more than 4.1 in (10 cm) and a median very close to zero.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The most snowfall in one month was 10.0 in (25 cm) in December 1960.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of the 2020 census, Alamogordo had a population of 30,898.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] 21.9% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.4% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] For every 100 females there were 99.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 98.5 males age 18 and over.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] 98.1% of residents lived in urban areas, while 1.9% lived in rural areas.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There were 13,377 households in Alamogordo, of which 26.4% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Of all households, 39.8% were married-couple households, 24.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 28.7% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] About 34.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There were 15,118 housing units, of which 11.5% were vacant.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The homeowner vacancy rate was 3.5% and the rental vacancy rate was 9.3%.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of the 2000 census, there were 13,704 households, and 9,728 families residing in the city.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The racial makeup of the city was 70.4% White; 5.6% African American, 1.1% Native American, 1.5% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, 12.1% from some other race, and 4.2% from two or more races.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 32.0% of the population.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There were 13,704 households, out of which 36.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 55.6% were married couples living together, 11.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.0% were non-families.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] 25.2% of all households were made up of individuals, and 8.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The average household size was 2.57 and the average family size was 3.07.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In the city the population was spread out, with 28.7% under the age of 18, 9.2% from 18 to 24, 29.7% from 25 to 44, 19.9% from 45 to 64, and 12.7% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] For every 100 females, there were 97.6 males.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.1 males.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 1999, the median income for a household in the city was $30,928, and the median income for a family was $35,673.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Males had a median income of $28,163 versus $18,860 for females.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The per capita income for the city was $14,662.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] About 13.2% of families and 16.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.9% of those under age 18 and 11.8% of those age 65 or over.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Previously Alamogordo had a German community due to the presence of the German Air Force at Holloman Air Force Base; in 1992 that air force made Holloman its main pilot training center in the United States.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Holloman was chosen due to its weather conditions.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There was a subdivision called "Little Germany" with houses that had German-style electrical outlets.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Deutsche Schule Alamogordo educated German children, as did the local schools.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Additionally area supermarkets had German cuisine.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] By 1999, there were about 1,110 German dependents and 900 German military personnel in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] By 2003 there were about 2,000 Germans in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] That year there were tensions between Americans and Germans since Germany chose not to join the U.S. in the Iraq War.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 2019, the German military withdrew from the base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Until the German Air Force left, Oktoberfest was celebrated annually in late September, hosted by the German Air Force at Holloman Air Force Base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The public was invited, and shuttle buses ran between Alamogordo and the base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo is the economic center of Otero County, with nearly half the Otero County population living within the city limits.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo today has very little manufacturing and has a primarily service and retail economy, driven by tourism, a large nearby military installation and a concentration of military retirees.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 2006 the per capita income in Otero County was $22,377 versus per capita income in New Mexico of $29,346.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo was founded as a company town to support the building of the El Paso and Northeastern Railroad, a portion of the transcontinental railway that was being constructed in the late 19th century.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Initially its main industry was timbering for railroad ties.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The railroad founders were also eager to found a major town that would persist after the railroad was completed; they formed the Alamogordo Improvement Company to develop the area, making Alamogordo an early example of a planned community.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Alamogordo Improvement Company owned all the land, platted the streets, built the first houses and commercial buildings, donated land for a college, and placed a restrictive covenant on each deed prohibiting the manufacture, distribution, or sale of intoxicating liquor.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Tourism became an important part of the local economy from the creation of White Sands National Monument in 1934.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Construction began on the Alamogordo Army Airfield (the present-day Holloman Air Force Base) in 1942, and the Federal government has been a strong presence in Alamogordo ever since.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Education has also been an important part of the local economy.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In addition to the local school system, Alamogordo is home to the New Mexico School for the Blind and Visually Impaired, founded in 1903, and a branch of New Mexico State University founded in 1958.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The largest non-government employer in the city is the Gerald Champion Regional Medical Center with 650 employees in 2008.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Holloman Air Force Base, located approximately 3 miles (4.8 km) west of the city limits, is the largest employer of Alamogordo residents, and has a major effect on the local economy.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] According to some estimates, Holloman accounts for half of the Alamogordo economy.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] According to the 49th Fighter Wing Public Affairs office, as of January 2008 Holloman directly employs 6,111 personnel with a gross payroll of $266 million.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It indirectly creates another 2,047 jobs with a payroll of $77 million.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The estimated amount spent in the community, including payroll, construction projects, supplies, services, health care, and education, is $482 million.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] An estimated 6,700 military retirees live in the area.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Counting both USAF and German Air Force personnel there are 1,383 active military and 1,641 military dependents living on base and 2,765 active military and 2,942 military dependents living off base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] After 27 years of training at Holloman, the German Air Force left in 2019.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] They relocated their pilot training to Sheppard Air Force Base in Texas.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Future Combat Systems is a wide-ranging modernization project of the US Army.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Much of the work will be done at Fort Bliss, with some at White Sands Missile Range and some at Holloman Air Force Base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo is expected to get some economic benefit due to its proximity to these three bases.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Otero County Economic Development Council is a nonprofit organization founded in 1984.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Its focus has generally been on job creation and recruiting and expanding businesses in Otero County, including helping them satisfy business regulations in New Mexico and lining up funding.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Its role expanded in 2000, when Alamogordo passed an Economic Development Gross Receipts Tax.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] OCEDC continues to work to attract businesses, but now it also helps develop the incentive packages that will be paid by the new tax, and a portion of the tax receipts go to fund OCEDC's operating expenses.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Formal economic development plans have been adopted by Alamogordo and by Otero County.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] OCEDC has recruited several new employers by using financial incentives.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] A 1-800-Flowers call center opened in November 2001 and received $1.25 million in city rent abatements, a 50% reduction in property taxes from Otero County, and $940,000 in plant training funds from the State of New Mexico.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] A Sunbaked Biscuits cookie factory opened in 2006 and received $800,000 in job-training incentives from the state.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] When the company went out of business in 2007, Marietta Baking took over the cookie factory and received interest-free loans, job-training incentives, and partial forgiveness of indebtedness for job creation.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] A branch office of PreCheck Inc., a company performing background checks of health-care workers, opened in 2006.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Otero County Film Office, an office of Otero County Economic Development Council, promotes film-making in Otero County by publicizing potential locations in the county and New Mexico's film financial incentive programs and by recruiting extras for film productions.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It sponsors the Desert Light Film Competition for middle and high school students to encourage learning about the film industry.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The 2007 film *Transformers* spent $5.5 million in New Mexico and $1 million in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are two amateur theatrical groups in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo Music Theatre produces two musical productions annually at the Flickinger Center for Performing Arts.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The NMSU-A Theatre on the Hill produces an annual spring performance for young audiences at the Rohovec Fine Arts Center on the New Mexico State University at Alamogordo campus, and an annual Fall performance for general audiences.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Earth Day Fair is held annually at Alameda Park Zoo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It features a butterfly release, a science fair, activities for children, and information booths from local health agencies and nonprofits.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Otero County Fair is held annually at the County Fairgrounds.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It features a rodeo, animal judging, food and game booths, and carnival rides.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Nonprofit and government agencies set up information booths in the exhibit hall.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Cottonwood Arts and Crafts Festival is put on each Labor Day Weekend in Alameda Park by the Alamogordo Chamber of Commerce.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It is primarily a showplace for vendors of handmade items, and also features music, entertainment, and food.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] White Sands Balloon Invitational is held annually.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Hot air balloons launch from the Riner-Steinhoff Soccerplex and from White Sands National Park and float over the Tularosa Basin.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] New Mexico Museum of Space History is a state museum with the International Space Hall of Fame.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Flickinger Center for Performing Arts is a 590-seat theater created in 1988 from a repurposed movie theater.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It hosts concerts and live theatrical performances by touring groups, and is the venue for the local amateur group Alamogordo Music Theater.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo Museum of History collects artifacts related to the history of Alamogordo and the Tularosa Basin.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It is a private museum, operated by the Tularosa Basin Historical Society.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Among notable items in the collection is a 47-star US Flag; New Mexico was the 47th state admitted to the Union, and US flags were made with 47 stars only for one month, until Arizona was admitted.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Museum shop has a large collection of local history books.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Historical Society also publishes its own series of monographs on local history, *Pioneer*.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] American Armed Forces Museum is a museum on U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 82 near Florida Avenue that opened in 2011.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It collects and displays all kinds of military memorabilia from all wars and military engagements.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Shroud Exhibit And Museum, located in White Sands Mall, showcases a full-sized back-lit photographic transparency of the Shroud of Turin, a religious relic believed by some to be the burial cloth of Jesus Christ.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] They also feature a working VP8 Image Analyzer, the only one in the world where one can walk in and interact with this old analog computer.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] This town was founded the same year (1898) that Secundo Pia took the first photograph of the Shroud which started the modern investigation into the Shroud.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 1977 in Albuquerque, they held the conference that resulted in the 1978 study of the Shroud with more scientists from New Mexico than any other state.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The displayed photograph was created from the 1978 photographs made by Barrie M.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Schwortz as part of the Shroud of Turin Research Project (STURP).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The displays include historical background materials, scientific information, kiosks with a variety of information, videos available for viewing and an exhibit of electronic image analysis of the shroud, among other interesting artifacts.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Alameda Park Zoo, the oldest zoo in the southwestern U.S., is located in the city.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Several Union-Apache battles were fought near Oliver Lee Memorial State Park.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Toy Train Depot, New Mexico's first railroad museum and home of America's Park Ride Train Museum.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] A sculpture called "The World's Largest Pistachio" is at McGinn's PistachioLand along U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Lady of the Mountain Run is held in December at the Griggs Sportsplex.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The race consists of a half marathon, 10K, 5K, or corporate cup relay, and raises money for the needs-based Lady of the Mountain Scholarship Fund at NMSU-Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Fun run/walks are popular in Alamogordo, although most are one-shot affairs put on as part of some larger event.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] One recurring event is Walk Out West, a 1.5-mile (2.4 km) walk held each October in Alameda Park Zoo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It incorporates a health fair, live music, and events for children.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] An offshoot of this is Dance Otero, an informal approach to ballroom dancing as a form of physical exercise that meets throughout the year.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Both programs are run through Otero PATH, a local nonprofit that encourages preventive measures for good health.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are a number of annual sports events.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Tommy Padilla Memorial Basketball Tournament is an annual event held in March.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It is an adult tournament that raises money for scholarships for Alamogordo High School students.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Gus Macker 3-on-3 Basketball Tournament is a national program that holds a tournament in Alamogordo each year in May.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Prior to 2008 it was hosted by the Alamogordo Chamber of Commerce, and since then by the City of Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The city receives 72% of the entry fees and 5% of the gross proceeds taken in by vendors.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The event is held annually at Washington Park in conjunction with Saturday in the Park and Armed Forces Day.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 2009 more than 233 teams participated in the tournament.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Several golf tournaments are held each year at Desert Lakes Golf Course, including the Robert W.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo's sole professional sports team is the White Sands Pupfish, a baseball team that played at Jim Griggs Field from 2011 to 2019, in the independent Pecos League, but did not play in a four-team, abridged 2020 season hosted in Houston due to pandemic concerns.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo has numerous small parks scattered through the city, and a few larger ones.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Not inside the city but nearby are several national and state parks.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Oliver Lee Memorial State Park is about 10 miles south on U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 54, offers camping, hiking, and picnicking.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] White Sands National Park is located about 15 miles (24 km) southwest of Alamogordo along U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The area is in the mountain-ringed Tularosa Basin valley area and comprises the southern part of a 275-square-mile (710 km2) field of white sand dunes composed of gypsum crystals.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Lincoln National Forest, whose headquarters are in Alamogordo, is a mountainous area that starts about 10 miles (16 km) northeast of Alamogordo and offers hiking, fishing, and camping.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Sidney Paul Gordon Shooting Range, located about 3 miles (4.8 km) north of town at 19 Rock Cliff Road in La Luz, is a supervised range with rifle, pistol, and archery ranges.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Several competitions are held at the range each month.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It is a charter city (also called a home rule city ), and the charter is included as Part I of the Code of Ordinances.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It has a Council-manager government form of government (called Commission/Manager in New Mexico).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are seven city commissioners, each elected from a district within the city, on staggered 4-year terms.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The city manager is considered the chief executive officer of the city and is tasked to enforce and implement the City Council's directives and policy.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The mayor is a member of the City Council.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of 2018, Richard Boss holds the position of mayor.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo's fiscal year ends on June 30 each year; thus Fiscal Year 2008 runs from July 1, 2007, through June 30, 2008.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Sources of City government income and their percentages of the whole were: gross receipts tax (31%), miscellaneous (23%), grants (22%), user fees (19%), and property tax (5%).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] New Mexico State University Alamogordo is a two-year community college established in 1958.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of 2016, it has approximately 1,800 students.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are two high schools (including the comprehensive Alamogordo High School), three middle schools, and 11 elementary schools in the Alamogordo Public School District.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Prior to 2008 there were two private schools in Alamogordo: Legacy Christian Academy and Father James B.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Hay Catholic School (the latter of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Las Cruces).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] A third private school, Imago Dei Academy, opened in August 2008 and provides a classical Christian education.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The New Mexico School for the Blind and Visually Impaired is a state school located in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The German government formerly operated the Deutsche Schule Alamogordo (German School) for children of German Air Force personnel stationed at the German tactical training center at Holloman Air Force Base until the 2019 withdrawal of German forces.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Following this, the aforementioned Imago Dei Academy purchased the building.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo Public Library serves Alamogordo and Otero County.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The library at New Mexico State University Alamogordo is also open to the public.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The main newspaper in Alamogordo is *Alamogordo Daily News* (ADN), owned by MediaNews Group.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] *ADN* is published six days a week; on Monday, when it does not appear, subscribers receive the *El Paso Times*.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] *ADN* also publishes *Hollogram*, a free weekly newspaper distributed at the nearby Holloman Air Force Base and covering happenings on base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There was no alternative newspapers published in Alamogordo but *The Ink*, a free Las Cruces monthly newspaper devoted to the arts, is distributed in the city.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] One television station, KVBA-LD, broadcasts from Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It has a religious format, and a weekly local news magazine broadcast Thursday through Saturday.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Cable television service is provided by Baja Broadband.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are two commercial radio broadcast companies, WP Broadcasting and Burt Broadcasting; each operates several stations in several formats.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There are two "listener-supported" radio stations that do not carry advertising but depend on sponsorships and donations.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] KLAG has a gospel music radio format and some live coverage of local events, including many remote broadcasts from civic events.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] KALH-LP is a low-power FM station that carries a variety radio format, network news on the hour, and local news on some hours.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The local NPR outlet is KRWG-FM in Las Cruces, which reaches Alamogordo through a local relay transmitter.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Several major motion pictures were filmed in or near Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The 2007 film *Transformers* was shot primarily at White Sands Missile Range, with additional filming at Holloman Air Force Base, both in the Alamogordo area.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Its 2009 sequel *Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen* also prominently featured these two military bases.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The 2009 film *Year One* was shot partly at White Sands National Monument, near Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo was one of the fourteen cities profiled in the 2005 documentary *14 Days in America*.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Otero County Film Office maintains a list of films shot partly or wholly in Alamogordo and Otero County.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In May 2013, Alamogordo's City Commission approved a deal for Canada-based film production company Fuel Industries to excavate the Atari landfill site.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Fuel Entertainment partnered with Xbox Entertainment Studios and Lightbox to make a documentary about the massive 1983 Atari video game burial, said to be one of the gaming culture's greatest urban legends.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] On April 26, 2014, video game archaeologists began sifting through years of trash from the old Alamogordo landfill.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The first batch of E.T. games was discovered after about three hours of digging, and hundreds more were found in the mounds of trash and dirt scooped by a backhoe.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In the deal between the City of Alamogordo and Fuel Entertainment regarding the excavation, Fuel Entertainment was to be given 250 games or 10 percent of what was found.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The major intercity surface routes from Alamogordo are U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Highways 54, 70, and 82, all of which are four-lane roads.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The major north–south street within the city is White Sands Boulevard.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Lee Memorial Relief Route, which is designated as U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 54 and 70, is a bypass road constructed to the west of the city in 2001 to relieve congestion on White Sands Boulevard.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 54 traverses through the north and south ends of the city.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] At the south end of the city, White Sands Boulevard is a major named street that merges into U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Lee Memorial Relief Route, running south to El Paso, Texas.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 54 in a southwestern direction towards Holloman Air Force Base, White Sands National Park, White Sands Missile Range, and Las Cruces.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] At the north end of the city, White Sands Boulevard and the Charles T.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Lee Memorial Relief Route become a merged U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Route 82 starts at the same point and runs east to Cloudcroft and the mountain communities of Otero County, and then to Artesia.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] 70 heads east through the mountains, and towards Ruidoso and Roswell, while U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] 54 heads north towards Carrizozo and keeps going north until it heads east again starting in Vaughn.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo-White Sands Regional Airport is the municipal airport located in the Alamogordo area.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] It is primarily used for general aviation.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] There is no longer scheduled commercial service from New Mexico Airlines, previously operated under a subsidy from the Essential Air Service program.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 2008, Greyhound Lines offered intercity bus service to Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of 2017, there was a daily shuttle van service between Alamogordo and El Paso International Airport.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Z-Trans is the mass transit system, providing paratransit and scheduled service within the city center and to White Sands Mall, Holloman Air Force Base and Inn of the Mountain Gods Resort & Casino in Mescalero.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Z-Trans is unusual in that it is privately owned (by Zia Therapy Center, a non-profit), although it does get some local and state subsidies.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Union Pacific provides railroad freight services.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Currently there is no intercity passenger train service.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] As of 2003, the Alamogordo city government was building a network of bike routes and walking routes.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] More information and maps are in the Alamogordo Comprehensive Plan.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In 2005, the New Mexico Rails-to-Trails Association operated a Rails to Trails project to convert old railroad beds to walking trails.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Its trail system in Otero County, the Cloud Climbing Rail Trail, is planned to eventually surround Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Electric power is supplied within the city by PNM Resources.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] PNM also provides electrical power in the Tularosa Basin, while Otero County Electric Cooperative, a member cooperative of Tri-State Generation and Transmission Association and of Touchstone Energy, serves other areas of the county.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Natural gas is supplied within the city by New Mexico Gas Company.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Severn Trent operates both the water and sewage treatment facilities for the City of Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Severn Trent maintains all water storage facilities, booster pump stations, city wells and treats the waste water to be re-used by the city to water the parks, Desert Lakes Golf Course and is sold to construction companies for dust control.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alamogordo has a dark sky ordinance to reduce the amount of light pollution in the night skies.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The ordinance was passed in 1990 to promote the growth and scientific productivity of Apache Point Observatory.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] City streetlights are high-pressure sodium vapor lamps.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Gerald Champion Regional Medical Center is a private not-for-profit 99-bed general hospital that serves the Alamogordo area.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The hospital is a shared military/civilian facility that is also the hospital for nearby Holloman Air Force Base.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The Otero County Community Health Council prepares a detailed health profile each year with many facts and figures about health in Otero County.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Otero County is ranked in the middle of most health rankings within the state.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] New Mexico is near the bottom of most national rankings; for example, it was 38th in the United Health Foundation 2007 report, but has been slowly improving (it was 40th in 2005).
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Among scientists, Edward Condon, a physicist and a past director of National Institute of Standards and Technology, was born in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alan Hale, an astronomer and co-discoverer of Comet Hale-Bopp, grew up in Alamogordo and lives in nearby Cloudcroft.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Mechem, a past governor and United States Senator from New Mexico, was born in Alamogordo, as was Cindy Chavez, a past member of the city council of San Jose, California.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Monica Kim Garza is a painter who was born in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Edward Lee Howard, a former CIA case agent who allegedly gave classified material to the Russians and later defected to the Soviet Union, was an Alamogordo native.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] In sports, professional soccer player Adam Frye, jockey Donna Barton Brothers, and former professional American football cornerback Conrad Hamilton were all born in Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Professional golf brothers Brad and Bart Bryant are from Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Alexis Duprey, crowned Miss New Mexico in 2013 and again in 2015, is from Alamogordo.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] Mai Shanley, who became Miss USA 1984, represented the city as Miss New Mexico USA.
[src:edward-condon/alamogordo-new-mexico] The lead singer of the 2020 Grammy-nominated Black Pumas, Eric Burton, grew up in Alamogordo and graduated from Alamogordo High School.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:edward-condon/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:edward-condon/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was the fourth director of the National Bureau of Standards (NIST) from 1945 to 1951.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In 1946, Condon was president of the American Physical Society, and in 1953 was president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] His case became a *cause célèbre* among those who opposed McCarthyism, especially scientists, and was one of the most prominent cases of its time, and he was defended by many prominent scientists, as well as President Harry Truman.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon became widely known in 1968 as principal author of the *Condon Report*, an official review funded by the United States Air Force that concluded that unidentified flying objects (UFOs) have prosaic explanations.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The lunar crater Condon is named for him.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Edward Uhler Condon was born on March 2, 1902, in Alamogordo, New Mexico, to William Edward Condon and Carolyn Uhler.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] His father was supervising the construction of a narrow-gauge railroad, many of which were built in the area by logging companies.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] After graduating from high school in Oakland, California in 1918, he worked as a journalist for three years at the *Oakland Inquirer* and other papers.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He then attended the University of California, Berkeley, initially joining the College of Chemistry; when he learned that his high school physics teacher had joined the faculty, he switched majors to take classes in theoretical physics.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon earned his bachelor's degree in three years and his doctorate in two.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] His Ph.D. thesis combined work by Raymond Thayer Birge on measuring and analyzing band spectral intensities and a suggestion by James Franck.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Thanks to a National Research Council fellowship, Condon studied at Göttingen under Max Born and at Munich under Arnold Sommerfeld.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Under the latter, Condon rewrote his Ph.D. thesis using quantum mechanics, creating the Franck–Condon principle.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] After seeing an ad in *Physical Review*, Condon worked in public relations at Bell Telephone Laboratories in fall 1927, in particular promoting their discovery of electron diffraction.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] While working at Bell Telephone Laboratories he also analyzed the frequency of word usage and related the results to the Weber–Fechner law in psychology.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon taught briefly at Columbia University and was associate professor of physics at Princeton University from 1928 to 1937, except for a year at the University of Minnesota.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Morse, he wrote *Quantum Mechanics*, the first English-language text on the subject in 1929.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Shortley, he wrote the *Theory of Atomic Spectra*, "a bible on the subject from the moment of its 1935 publication".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was associate director of research at the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh, beginning in 1937, where he established research programs in nuclear physics, solid-state physics, and mass spectrometry.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He then headed the company's research on microwave radar development.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He also worked on the equipment used to isolate uranium for use in atomic bombs.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He served as a consultant to the National Defense Research Committee during World War II and helped organize MIT's Radiation Laboratory.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On May 11, 1940, Condon showcased the "Nimatron", an electro-mechanical machine for playing Nim, at the 1940 New York World Fair.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In 1943, Condon joined the Manhattan Project.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Within six weeks, he resigned as a result of conflicts about security with General Leslie R.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] General Groves had objected when Condon's superior J.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Robert Oppenheimer held a discussion with the director of the project's Metallurgical Lab (Arthur Compton) at the University of Chicago.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In his resignation letter, he said he felt he would be more useful to the war effort by staying at Westinghouse, explaining that the security measures he found at Los Alamos so concerned him that he would become depressed and ineffective.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was upset that Oppenheimer did not stand up to Groves, but he did not know that Oppenheimer had yet to receive his own security clearance.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] From August 1943 to February 1945, Condon worked as a part-time consultant at Berkeley on the separation of U-235 and U-238.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1944.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In June 1945, Condon was among many prominent American scientists invited to attend a celebration of the 220th anniversary of the founding of the Russian Academy of Sciences to be held in Moscow.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] When Groves learned of this, he contacted Condon's employers at Westinghouse, and explained that he believed this would be dangerous from the perspective of possibly revealing information about the atomic bomb work that was still on-going.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon attempted to contact the White House in protest.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Subsequently, Groves requested that the State Department revoke Condon's passport, which they did.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Following the war, Condon played a leading role in organizing scientists to lobby for civilian control of atomic energy rather than military control under strict security.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He worked as science adviser to Senator Brien McMahon, chairman of the Senate Special Committee on Atomic Energy, which wrote the McMahon-Douglas Act, enacted in August 1946, that created the Atomic Energy Commission, placing atomic energy under civilian control.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Adopting an internationalist viewpoint, Condon favored international scientific cooperation and joined the American-Soviet Science Society.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1947.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Commerce Secretary (and former U.S. vice president) Henry A.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Wallace came to know Condon and in October 1945 recommended him as director of the National Bureau of Standards (NBS, now known as NIST).
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The Senate confirmed his nomination without opposition.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon served as NBS director until 1951.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was also president of the American Physical Society in 1946.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was also either a member or associated with the Independent Citizens Committee of the Arts, Sciences and Professions (ICCASP).
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1949.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] During the 1940s, Condon's security clearance status was repeatedly questioned, reviewed, and re-established.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Edgar Hoover wrote a letter intended for President Truman that named several senior government officials as part of a Soviet network.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] It described Condon as "nothing more or less than an espionage agent in disguise".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] (Decades later Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan called it "baseless corridor talk".) The Truman administration ignored Hoover's charges.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On March 21, 1947, Truman signed United States Executive Order 9835 AKA the "Loyalty Order".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Parnell Thomas, head of the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC), furnished information to the *Washington Times-Herald* that denigrated his loyalty in two articles published.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Thomas had several reasons to make a prominent case of Condon.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The Department of Commerce cleared Condon of disloyalty charges on February 24, 1948.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Nevertheless, a HUAC report dated March 2, 1948 stated, "It appears that Dr.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On March 5, 1948, Representative George MacKinnon (Rep-MN) stated: "Mr.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Speaker, today's paper carries the story that the Secretary of Commerce, Mr. [W.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Averell] Harriman, has refused to respond to a congressional subpoena to supply information with respect to one Dr.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon." The *Post* also objected to an alternative proposal to send files on the Condon case to the top-level "Loyalty Review Board" in the Civil Service Commission.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The Commerce Department's own loyalty board had already cleared Condon, and the *Post* argued that this decision should stand.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On March 8, 1948, Representative Chester E.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Holifield (Dem-CA) noted: "... calling the attention of the Members to H.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] 4641, a bill which I introduced December 4, 1947.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The purpose of this bill is to prescribe the procedures of investigating committees of the Congress and to protect the rights of parties under investigation by such committees.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] If this bill could be enacted, it would extend to a world-famous scientist, such as Dr.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon, the same protection which is now available to a chicken thief or a traffic violator; that is, the right of defense against his accusers.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Character assassination under the cloak of congressional immunity by a Member of Congress or a Congressional committee is a dangerous and abominable travesty." On March 9, 1948, Representative Glen H.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Taylor (Dem-ID), then Progressive Party vice presidential candidate, Representative Emanuel Celler (Dem-NY), Representative Leo Isacson (ALP-NY) all condemn the recurring attacks on Condon by the committee.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Defenders included Albert Einstein and Harold Urey.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The entire physics department of Harvard and numerous professional organizations wrote Truman on Condon's behalf.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The Emergency Committee of Atomic Scientists held a dinner on April 12, 1948, to demonstrate support, with nine Nobel Prize winners among the sponsors.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The National Academy of Sciences, by contrast, considered only a statement criticizing HUAC's procedures rather than defending Condon.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Despite widespread support among its members (275 to 35), the National Academy of Sciences' leadership did not release a statement, and instead opted to speak privately with Rep.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On July 15, 1948, the Atomic Energy Commission granted Condon a security clearance, allowing him to access classified information at NIST.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In September 1948, at the Annual Meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS), President Truman, with Condon sitting nearby on the dais, denounced Rep.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Thomas and HUAC on the grounds that vital scientific research "may be made impossible by the creation of an atmosphere in which no man feels safe against the public airing of unfounded rumors, gossip and vilification".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He called HUAC's activities "the most un-American thing we have to contend with today.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] It is the climate of a totalitarian country".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon opposed any cooperation with Congressional attempts to identify security risks within the scientific community.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He criticized Thomas and the HUAC for holding closed hearings and then leaking information that denigrated his loyalty and that of other scientists.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He said that the committee denied his and his colleagues' requests for public hearings so they could respond.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Murrow had colleague Don Hollenbeck contribute to the innovative media-review program, *CBS Views the Press* over the radio network's flagship station WCBS.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] With his record finally cleared in 1951, Condon left government to become head of research and development for the Corning Glass Works.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He said his $14,000 annual government salary was his reason for the move.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Two Republican Congressmen asserted that Condon was being investigated as a security risk and was leaving "under fire", a charge the Secretary of Commerce Charles Sawyer denied.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In 1951, Condon served as president of the Philosophical Society of Washington.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On December 27, 1951, Condon was elected to head the AAAS in 1953.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In September 1952, Condon, in testimony before a Congressional committee, had his first opportunity to deny under oath all charges of disloyalty that had been made against him.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The HUAC concluded in its annual report for 1952 that Condon was unsuited for a security clearance because of his "propensity for associating with persons disloyal or of questionable loyalty and his contempt for necessary security regulations".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On December 30, 1952, Condon assumed the presidency of the AAAS at its annual meeting, where, according to the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists*, "The tremendous ovation by his fellow members accompanying his induction was a further affirmation of their faith in his loyalty and integrity".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Five months later Condon's clearance was revoked as was standard when someone left government service.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was granted a security clearance once more on July 12, 1954.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] It was announced on October 19 and then suspended by Secretary of the Navy Charles S.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Vice President Nixon took credit for the suspension, and the Atomic Scientists of Chicago charged "political abuse of the national security system", though Secretary Thomas denied Nixon had played a role.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon withdrew his application for clearance and in December resigned from Corning because the company was seeking government research contracts and he lacked the clearance necessary for participating in military research.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] After citing the security reviews he had passed over the years, he said: "I am unwilling to continue a potentially indefinite series of reviews and re-reviews".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Corning had paid Condon's clearance-related legal expenses while he worked there.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In 1958, Condon wrote that his decision reflected his belief that the Eisenhower administration "was committed by policy to the persecution of scientists, or, at the very least, to a callous indifference toward what others were doing to attack and discredit them.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] I decided the situation was hopeless, and that I had done all that could be reasonably expected of me in having resisted these forces for seven long years".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Years later, Carl Sagan reported how Condon described one encounter with a loyalty review board.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon, it says here that you have been at the forefront of a revolutionary movement in physics called ... quantum mechanics.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] It strikes this hearing that if you could be at the forefront of one revolutionary movement ... you could be at the forefront of another".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon said he replied: "I believe in Archimedes' Principle, formulated in the third century B.C.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] I believe in Kepler's laws of planetary motion, discovered in the seventeenth century.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] I believe in Newton's laws ..." and continued with a catalog of scientists from earlier centuries, including the Bernoulli, Fourier, Ampère, Boltzmann, and Maxwell.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He once said privately: "I join every organization that seems to have noble goals.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was professor of physics at Washington University in St.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Louis from 1956 to 1963 and then at the University of Colorado Boulder from 1963, where he was also a fellow of the Joint Institute for Laboratory Astrophysics, until retiring in 1970.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] From 1966 to 1968, Condon directed Boulder's UFO Project, known as the Condon Committee.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was chosen for his eminence and his lack of any stated position on UFOs.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He later wrote that he agreed to head the project "on the basis of appeals to duty to do a needed public service" on the part of the U.S.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Air Force Office of Scientific Research.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Its 1968 final report – which drew on Project Blue Book information from the USAF, as well as reports collected by two civilian organisations – concluded that unidentified flying objects had prosaic explanations.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was also president of the American Institute of Physics and the American Association of Physics Teachers in 1964.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He was President of the Society for Social Responsibility in Science (1968–69) and was co-chair of the National Committee for a Sane Nuclear Policy (1970).
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He co-edited the *Handbook of Physics* with Hugh Odishaw of the University of Arizona.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] He received the Frederic Ives Medal awarded by the Optical Society in 1968.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] On his retirement, his colleagues honored him with the publication of a *Festschrift*.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In 1922, Condon married Chicago-born Emilie/Emma Honzik (1899–1974), who was a translator from the Czech language.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Their son Joseph Henry Condon (February 15, 1935 – January 2, 2012) was a physicist (Ph.D., Northwestern University) and engineer, who worked at Bell Labs on digital telephone switches and co-invented the Belle chess computer.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon was a Quaker, and a self-described "liberal".
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon died on March 26, 1974, twenty-four days after his 72nd birthday, in Boulder Colorado Community Hospital.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] His wife Emma died just over 7 months later.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) gives an annual award named for Condon.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The Condon Award recognizes distinguished achievements in written exposition in science and technology at NIST.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] The crater Condon on the Moon is named in his honor.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] Condon's colleague Lewis Branscomb said of him, "Watergate came as no surprise to Edward Condon, nor did its aftermath.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] I imagine he would like to have lived to see the outcome of the impeachment inquiry.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] But Condon understood and paid his share of the price of liberty.
[src:edward-condon/edward-condon] In the 2023 film *Oppenheimer*, directed by Christopher Nolan, Condon was portrayed by actor Olli Haaskivi.
